.  These observatories were usually situated underground (there were a few exceptions) so that the conditions of earth could be simulated.  Since the basic structure of the moon is honeycombed, the interior above the frozen zone (see diagram on moon) takes
 the form of numerous caverns connected by a maze of natural tunnels formed by the pressure of gases.  The caverns contain the trapped gas.  The builders of the observatories use these caverns for the skeleton of their underground structures.  Because of t
he drying up process of the moon's composition more gas accumulates underneath the bottom of large craters than it does under flat land.  Because of the suction involved with craters the gas rises closer to the surface beneath the crater floor, and because
 of this, the caverns containing the gases under the crater are larger and more accesable.  With the aid of a small device attached to the underside of the builders' spacecraft he hovers near the crater floor and sends beams of a condensed type of first st
ate energy through the floor down into the caverns or gas pockets.  Through this process he is able to convert the gases into an immediate change of state without any chemical reaction (such as an explosion) resulting.  The gases are converted to a low qua
lity of first state energy that is directed into the core of the planet where through the natural process it will be utilized by the moon and therefore the balance will not be lost.  The caverns are now devoid of gases and are ready for the construction of
 the interior.  Certain walls are removed and caverns enlarged by energy transferences, and then the caverns are coated with a solution that removes all danger or friction.  (Most of the energy used is first state which is non-combustible, but this solutio
n is applied as a safety measure to guard against natural occurrences such as large meteors.  Then the actual building begins.  They are sprayed with a solutions which in a small amount of time solidifies and expands into }
