of matter through space brought on by the pressure of the planes.  While no plane relies on another for existence, in order for certain conditions to continue in a plane such as earth's the pressure exertedon the earth by the planes gives the stimulation t
o the earth plane to carry out it's function.  A plane cannot be destroyed by another plane but it's conditions can be changed through the influence of another plane.  In dealing with gravity on the earth plane four planes are involved: the time plane, the
 earth plane, the earth's conjunctive plane, and the earth's overlapping plane.  Gravity is one of the most complicated systems on the plane of earth.  It is for this reason that I will not attempt to go into detail on this system.  I will, however, explai
n a few of the more major points.  The basic condition on the earth plane that holds all else in a true pattern on the earth plane is time plus speed equals distance (T \'96 S = D).  On the earth's overlapping plane this holding condition is speed minus time 
equals time (S \'96 T = T).  The holding condition of the earth's conjunctive plane is distance plus speed plus time equals distance plus speed plus time (D+S+T = D+S+T).  Each one of these planes and their holding conditions form the balance needed to create
 the gravity as we know it on the plane of earth.  The time plane contains no holding condition, as it is the neutral plane needed in the balancing of all planes.  Gravity is created by the conflicting influences of motion and time.  Speed, distance, and t
ime are all under the laws of motion, causing the influences of S. D. And T. to create motion.  }
