 and these conditions are all under the law of motion, space must be totally consistent in it's proportion in order to enable it to support the pressures exerted by the law of motion.  Space is sensitive to mass and responds to the movement of any collecti
ve mass.  The area of space influenced by two or more opposite masses is fixed space.  The space in which no mass exists, such as between galaxies, is free space.  There are different levels of fixed space depending upon the amount of opposite mass present
 and their distance from a given point in space, and also from each other.  The area between solar systems contains some degree of fixed space, but the space between galaxies is almost toatlly free space.  Space is in a pulsating state, as is all of the un
iverse.  Without this pulsation of the universe the law of the planes, all that pushes out from itself must eventually push into itself, could not exist.  The pulsation of space is unique in that there is no shifting involved.  All else in the universe mus
t shift it's energy in some way in order to pulsate as a whole.  Space does not comply with this as it's energy content is not subject to space, rather space is subject to the energy.  }
